<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFFFFFCCFF89263BFE8D8CC3" blockId="108.[94,623,918,1763]" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">
Handley (1987) recognized two subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFFFFFCCFF8C2655FEC08D65" baseAuthorityName="Gervais" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[126,331,1095,1118]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Artibeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cinereus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFF8C2655FEC08D65" box="[126,331,1095,1118]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">Artibeus cinereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but did not discuss their distinguishing characteristics. Whereas specimens he identified as 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFE8E2693FE058DA3" box="[380,398,1153,1176]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFE512693FE3B8DA3" box="[419,432,1153,1176]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">c</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFFFFFCCFE372693FDAC8DA3" baseAuthorityName="Gervais" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[453,551,1153,1176]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Artibeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cinereus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFE372693FDAC8DA3" box="[453,551,1153,1176]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">cinereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were listed from localites in central Amazonia on both sides of the river, specimens he assigned to 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFF7726CBFF1C8DCB" box="[133,151,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFF4226CBFF368DCB" box="[176,189,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">c</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFF2726CBFEF38DCB" box="[213,376,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">quadrivittatus</emphasis>
were from eastern Venezuela, Surinam, eastern Amazonia, and the northernmost part of the Brazilian Atlantic forest. Presumably, our material is referable to the latter taxon, the type locality of which is Surinam (
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFFFFFCCFEAE277EFD808CB8" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[348,523,1388,1411]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson, 1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978). Measurements of the holotype of 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFE08279BFF1C8C85" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">quadrivittatus</emphasis>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFFFFFCCFEC127B4FE548C86" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[307,479,1446,1469]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962)</bibRefCitation>
fall entirely within the range of variation in our sample from Paracou.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FAA1E8DFFFFFFCCFF8927ECFBEC8DE0" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFFFFFCCFF8927ECFBE98D7F" blockId="108.[94,623,918,1763]" lastBlockId="108.[670,1199,918,1243]" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: We recorded 41 captures (possibly including some recaptures) of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFFFFFCCFFAC242BFEBB8F6B" baseAuthorityName="Gervais" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[94,304,1593,1616]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Artibeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="108" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cinereus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFFFFFCCFFAC242BFEBB8F6B" box="[94,304,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">Artibeus cinereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Paracou, of which 37 were in groundÂ­level mistnets, 1 was in an elevated mistnet, and 3 were at roosts. Of the 37 groundÂ­level mistnet captures, 1 was in wellÂ­drained primary forest, 5 were in swampy primary forest, 3 were in creekside primary forest, 1 was in a treefall opening in primary forest, 22 were in manmade clearings, and 5 were over roadside puddles. The single example taken in an elevated mistnet was captured 5â€“8 m above the ground in the subcanopy of swampy primary forest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFFFFFCCFD492659FBEC8DE0" blockId="108.[670,1199,918,1243]" pageId="108" pageNumber="108">
